---
// ramelteon — CONTEXT page (deferred from Phase 5). NOT a graded remedy: ramelteon is a
// prescription drug, so it sits outside Somnary's graded corpus of OTC / natural remedies. No tier
// badge, no evidence-gate chips — the ContextBanner marks it as background. The one genuine efficacy
// claim (AASM's weak recommendation FOR ramelteon, vs its weak recommendation AGAINST OTC melatonin)
// is cited to the 2017 AASM guideline, verified firsthand. Mechanism / regulatory facts are
// attributed to the FDA prescribing information (Rozerem) rather than asserted uncited.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'Sateia MJ, Buysse DJ, Krystal AD, et al. Clinical Practice Guideline for the Pharmacologic Treatment of Chronic Insomnia in Adults (AASM). J Clin Sleep Med. 2017;13(2):307–349.',
    finding:
      'the american academy of sleep medicine issues a weak recommendation FOR ramelteon in sleep-onset insomnia — and, in the same guideline, a weak recommendation AGAINST over-the-counter melatonin for sleep-onset or sleep-maintenance insomnia.',
    pmid: '27998379',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.6470',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="ramelteon (Rozerem): the prescription melatonin-receptor drug, in context | Somnary"
  description="ramelteon is a prescription melatonin-receptor agonist, not an over-the-counter supplement. Somnary doesn't grade it. what it is, how it differs from OTC melatonin, and why it's a decision for your prescriber."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/ramelteon"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · prescription sleep medicine</p>
      <h1 class="title">ramelteon<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="dek">
        ramelteon (brand name Rozerem) is the prescription cousin of the melatonin you can buy off a
        shelf. because it's a prescription drug, it sits outside the over-the-counter and natural
        corpus Somnary grades. so this page is background, not a grade.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="ramelteon is prescription-only, so it isn't scored on Somnary's S–F scale. that scale is for remedies you can choose and buy yourself; a prescription is a decision you and a clinician make together."
    />

    <!-- what it is -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what it is</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          ramelteon is a <strong>melatonin-receptor agonist</strong>: it acts on the same MT1 and MT2
          receptors your own melatonin uses to signal the brain toward sleep. Unlike the older
          sleeping pills (the &ldquo;Z-drugs&rdquo; and benzodiazepines), it doesn't act on the GABA
          system, and per its FDA-approved prescribing information it is <strong>not a scheduled
          controlled substance</strong>. It isn't classed as habit-forming in the way those
          sedatives are. It was approved in the United States in 2005 for insomnia characterised by
          difficulty <strong>falling asleep</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- how it differs from OTC melatonin -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">how it differs from the melatonin on the shelf</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          This is the useful part, and where the evidence actually points somewhere. The American
          Academy of Sleep Medicine's 2017 guideline reviewed both, and split them: it issues a
          <strong>weak recommendation <em>for</em> ramelteon</strong> in sleep-onset insomnia, and in
          the same document a <strong>weak recommendation <em>against</em> over-the-counter
          melatonin</strong> for either falling asleep or staying asleep.<Fn n={1} />
        </p>
        <p>
          Both recommendations are &ldquo;weak&rdquo; (the evidence is modest either way), but the
          direction differs. A prescription drug is manufactured to a fixed, verified dose and studied
          as a specific product; an OTC melatonin supplement is not, and its actual content can swing
          wildly from the label (a problem covered on the
          <a href="/r/melatonin">melatonin page</a> and the
          <a href="/melatonin-children">children page</a>). Same receptor, very different products.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- why Somnary doesn't grade it -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">why Somnary doesn't grade it</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Somnary grades the things a reader can weigh and buy on their own: over-the-counter
          supplements, botanicals, and behavioural or environmental interventions. A prescription
          medicine isn't that kind of choice: it's prescribed, dosed, and monitored by a clinician
          who knows your history. Putting an S–F letter on it would imply you could pick it up like a
          supplement, which you can't and shouldn't. So we describe it and stop there. The full rule
          for what is and isn't in scope lives in the <a href="/methodology">methodology</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- talk to your prescriber -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">if you're considering it, this is a prescriber conversation</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Because ramelteon is prescription-only, the safety details are handled by the clinician who
          prescribes it. That's the point of it being prescription. Two things worth knowing going
          in, per its prescribing information: it <strong>should not be combined with fluvoxamine</strong>
          (an antidepressant that sharply raises ramelteon levels), and it is generally
          <strong>avoided in severe liver disease</strong>. Bring your full medication list
          (including any supplements) to that conversation, and don't start, stop, or combine it with
          anything on your own.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>

